        <para>
            <graphic fileref="images/editor_top_basic.png" align="center" valign="middle" width="1000px"/>
        </para>
        <para>Inside the frame, you will find a number of tabs and some buttons.</para>
        <para>The input forms are currently organised into a numbers of tab-sets. When you open the editor, you land inside the Basic Input Forms, the forms that are designed to make it possible to catalogue most bibliographical items fairly quickly. 
            This tab divides into three subtabs, one for Publication, one for Container, and one for Contents.</para>
        <para>Clicking on the button above the tabs to the left takes you to a new set of tabs. The next tab is called "Citation Forms" and the next again "Content Description Forms." The last set of tabs is called --- "Remaining Forms." 
            This awkward label cover a number of fields mainly of administrative interest, but also such useful fields as the Note field, the Related Items fields and the Identifiers. </para>
        <para>The button then completes the circle and allows you to go back to the Basic Input Forms. (A faster way of moving from tab-set to tab-set will be implemented.)</para>
        <para>"Citation Forms," "Content Description Forms" and "Remaining Forms" more or less cover the same ground as the Basic Input Forms, only in more detail, offering more specialised input options. 
            If you are inputting something in the Basic Input Forms, you may switch to the other input forms and complete your record there. What you have input on the other forms may not be visible on the Basic Input Forms, but it is saved nonetheless.</para>
